" Usage

" INTERACTIVE ENTITY LIST
" ------------------------
" To display the interactive entity list in the 
" current window, enter normal mode and type
"
"   <Leader>ht
"
" for most users, that's \ht
"
" You can double-click entities to copy-and-
" paste them back to the buffer you were just 
" working on, or you can just position the cursor 
" over an entity and press 'r' (or Enter) to do 
" the same.
"
" Press 'b' or 'B' to cycle forwards or backwards 
" through the set of available bases. HTML 
" recognizes three entity formats, e.g.,
"
"     dec: &#928; / hex: &#x3D6; / ent: &piv;
"
" (i.e., decimal, hexidecimal, and entity/
"  friendly name).
"
" Use 'q' or <ESC> to quit the buffer. It will 
" be destroyed and the last working buffer will 
" be displayed instead.

" INLINE ENTITY LOOKUP
" ------------------------
" You can quickly translate typeable characters 
" to their HTML character entity by using the 
" QuickLookup.
"
" Invoke QuickLookup from normal mode by typing
"
"   <Leader>hT
"
" for most users, that's \hT
"
" In the command window, you should see 
" 
"   >> Please enter a character: 
"
" Type just the single character you want 
" translated (i.e., '&' (without the quotes))  
" and its entity reference will be inserted into 
" your working buffer at the cursor (note that 
" you don't have to hit return after typing the 
" character to be translated).

" TOGGLE ENTITY LIST VISIBILITY
" ------------------------
" You can obviously map <Leader>ht to any key 
" command you want, but you can also map a 
" toggle function, which creates or destroys 
" the interactive entity list depending on 
" whether not its already visible.
"
" Personally, I like using Alt-Shift-Number 
" combinations to map all my "smart" buffers 
" (i.e., Alt-Shift-1 toggles an ASCII chart 
" (chartab.vim), Alt-Shift-2 toggles the 
" QuickFix window, Alt-Shift-3 toggles 
" the NERD tree, Alt-Shift-4 toggles a 
" project browser, and Alt-Shift-5 toggles 
" the HTML entity list).
"
" To map the toggle function to Alt-Shift-5
" (Alt-%, technically), for instance, add the 
" following command to your vimrc startup script:
"
"   nmap <M-%> <Plug>HCT_ToggleLookup

" ------------------------------------------
" User Interface

" Startup
" ------------------------
" This allows the user to avoid loading this 
" plugin by defining plugin_htmlchartable; this 
" also prevents the script from being re-loaded
if exists("plugin_htmlchartable_vim")
  finish
endif
